					Re: Gay By Choice
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1725058">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>DmitrytheWizzy</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=2f1c020babc86faf2681e53c14599bb3&amp;p=1725043#post1725043" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Changing her to bisexual is just changing descriptions to suit your argument.  She her self is lesbian.  Self description is the only description that matters.  You cannot externally change what she is to suit your argument.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>This still feels like an argument you want to be having with someone else. I readily admit self description never occurred to me. If you read any of the transgender threads you will see that I'm a very simple person and the whole identity issue is above my head.<br />
<br />
You have a tendency to link your arguments with things you know are offensive to rile people up and catch them off guard. In this case you are making use of the belief that people aren't born gay, and are simply pretending to be for one social reason or another.<br />
<br />
Buy if you ignore all the baggage and think about it logically, the presence of one choice implies that there must be another. If you can choose to be gay then you can choose to be straight, not everyone is capable of this, and those that are are defined with a certain word. <br />
<br />
Although if you want to get technical, this word isn't quite adequate either, but I can't choose to be gay any more than someone else can choose to be straight. Kudos for those that can, but their existence does not nullify the experiences of everyone else. It just means people are diverse and you cannot easily sort them between two binary categories.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
