				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Gay By Choice
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1725135">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Elasto</strong>
					
				</div>
				<div class="message">Yup. I've read studies like this before and it only strengthens the point: Men have no control over what they are turned on by - and women are sometimes so disconnected they don't even realise what turns them on; so given that your sexual orientation is determined by what turns you on rather than who you sleep with it's obviously even less of a choice for them.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I would simply say that women are stimulated differently than men.  They may not realize when their genitals are stimulated, and their genitals are equipped to be ready for many kinds of sexual activity whether there is a conscious desire or not.  What motivates the conscious desire is unknown.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				Diamond is a tireless researcher. The study that led to her book has been going on for more than 10 years. During that time, she has followed the erotic attractions of nearly 100 young women who, at the start of her work, identified themselves as either lesbian or bisexual or refused a label. From her analysis of the many shifts they made between sexual identities and from their detailed descriptions of their erotic lives, <b>Diamond argues that for her participants, and quite possibly for women on the whole, desire is malleable, that it cannot be captured by asking women to categorize their attractions at any single point, that to do so is to apply a male paradigm of more fixed sexual orientation.</b> Among the women in her group who called themselves lesbian, to take one bit of the evidence she assembles to back her ideas, just one-third reported attraction solely to women as her research unfolded. And with the other two-thirds, the explanation for their periodic attraction to men was not a cultural pressure to conform but rather a genuine desire.
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Also, I don't think that these studies included self-identified male bisexuals.  I know they exist but have no idea whether they are straights or gays who simply act occasionally against their instincts.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
